ontent><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2008/08/some-site-changes.html' title='Some site changes'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=5714454928317003214&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/5714454928317003214/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/5714454928317003214'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/5714454928317003214'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-96569256936500591</id><published>2007-11-21T18:46:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2008-09-03T14:00:37.060-07:00</updated><title type='text'>I am the master of my domain</title><content type='html'>I purchased a domain on the internet. Land is cheap out there on the internet these days. If you visit my domain, which is called www.primaryproductivity.org, at this exact moment you will find nothing substantive, just some links and ads from GoDaddy.com (the registrar that I purchased my name from) that serve as a kind of placeholder until I get a host and some of my own content built there. I don't know what I'll do in this domain. Probably I'll start posting my work there - so these blogs will probably move over there eventually, and hopefully a new blog on my graduate research experiences will develop, and I can keep interesting electronic media and info there for people to access. I hope it will all come together as something interesting over time.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The name.... is dorky, but I like it, and if you don't like it you should stop and think about this: Primary productivity is defined as the movement of carbon from the atmosphere into living organisms over time. Essentially, it is the rate of photosynthesis, and 99% of all life on earth depends on the products of this directly or indirectly. This process is performed mainly by vascular plants on land and by algae in the oceans. You, and all the other beings that grow and reproduce by eating plants and other animals are another result of primary productivity. So, what I'm saying here is that this blog is about YOU. And me. Its about &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;us&lt;/span&gt;.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2007/11/i-am-master-of-my-domain.html' title='I am the master of my domain'/><link rel='related' href='http://www.primaryproductivity.org' title='I am the master of my domain'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=96569256936500591&amp;isPopup=true' title='1 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/96569256936500591/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/96569256936500591'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/96569256936500591'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-7415876037375648619</id><published>2007-11-07T18:06:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2007-11-07T18:09:03.610-08:00</updated><title type='text'>The metabolic theory of ecology...</title><content type='html'>...is cool.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Really cool.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2007/11/metabolic-theory-of-ecology.html' title='The metabolic theory of ecology...'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=7415876037375648619&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/7415876037375648619/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/7415876037375648619'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/7415876037375648619'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-801864217450091145</id><published>2007-10-16T16:00:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2007-10-16T17:39:28.251-07:00</updated><title type='text'>My life is over, but I will continue to blog about it</title><content type='html'>I have yet again postponed real life to become a student for several more years, this time a "graduate student" at the University of Utah. I'm joining an &lt;a href="http://www.biology.utah.edu/bowling/index.html"&gt;ecosystem ecology lab&lt;/a&gt; that focuses on studying biosphere-atmosphere interactions, the carbon cycle at multiple scales, and blah blah pollution blah feedbacks to blah-bla isotopic blablablah climate change bla-blah blah blablah. I don't know specifically what part of this research I'll be latching on to and developing into a thesis project yet, but as long as I keep sitting at my desk reading journal articles, gazing blankly out the window, reading some more, thinking about the metabolic theory of ecology, staring at the ceiling, reading all this weeks Nature articles that apply to my field, sending emails to professors, pondering, going to get coffee and then coming back to my desk for more reading, thinking, making lists of papers to read, staring, and so on, as I am currently doing almost every day of the week, I'll probably come up with something good in a few years.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;So, what does that mean for this blog? I don't really know. I'll sit at my desk and think about it. One thing I do know is that I like this blog and I want to keep writing here, or at least continue writing in the same vein - that is, writing creatively about the things I do on a daily basis while bringing up the scientific thinking and processes behind it in a clear and interesting way. It helps me explain things to myself (and possibly others) and prevents me from getting desperately bored with my life in academia. I also like posting pictures.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;One idea I have is to give this blog a makeover and turn it into my graduate student blog. I could archive the seed collecting blog posts somewhere, rearrange the links, change the title, make a few other minor adjustments, and then continue my blogging career. I could also just orphan this one and start a completely new blog. I don't know.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Anyways, here is a picture of an old broken-down truck sitting in a field at the &lt;a href="http://entrada.utah.edu/"&gt;Entrada field station&lt;/a&gt;, a new U of U research facility on the Dolores river that I visited last week.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://bp1.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RxVYgxSrcsI/AAAAAAAAACM/7_P095HhRmo/s1600-h/Entrada_070030.jpeg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://bp1.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RxVYgxSrcsI/AAAAAAAAACM/7_P095HhRmo/s320/Entrada_070030.jpeg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5122097471214547650" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2007/10/my-life-is-over-but-i-will-continue-to.html' title='My life is over, but I will continue to blog about it'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=801864217450091145&amp;isPopup=true' title='4 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/801864217450091145/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/801864217450091145'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/801864217450091145'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-1477109826992987323</id><published>2007-05-24T19:32:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2007-05-24T19:49:22.725-07:00</updated><title type='text'>So...Matthew has his own blog now. Whatever.</title><content type='html'>So, Matthew Utley stopped posting on this blog and went out and got his own blog.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Fine Matthew.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Do whatever you want, Matthew, but don't forget that your blogging career started here at this humble blog. I hope I don't crawl out of a dumpster in 5 years and see you walking down the street being followed by a herd of adoring fans. I hope you don't look over and see me in my greasy rags, stinking of selenium, muttering about &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Polygala subspinosa&lt;/span&gt;, then turn to your fans and whisper "I used to blog with him...but he... he kind of lost it...", then  shake your head and walk away.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You better do a guest post this summer.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Whatever Matthew...&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://bp1.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RlZORkcbF7I/AAAAAAAAACE/AbrkpldSrF0/s1600-h/img_0561.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://bp1.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RlZORkcbF7I/AAAAAAAAACE/AbrkpldSrF0/s320/img_0561.jpg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5068324494399707058" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.aviaryhabitats.blogspot.com/"&gt;(This is the link to Matthew's blog)&lt;/a&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2007/05/somathew-has-his-own-blog-now-whatever.html' title='So...Matthew has his own blog now. Whatever.'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=1477109826992987323&amp;isPopup=true' title='2 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/1477109826992987323/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/1477109826992987323'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/1477109826992987323'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-6275348070253493894</id><published>2007-05-21T21:04:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2007-05-24T21:04:51.784-07:00</updated><title type='text'>I still love you Astragalus</title><content type='html'>Dear &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Astragalus&lt;/span&gt;,&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I know I've been spending time with other genera and admiring the assets of all sorts of beautiful plants lately, but I still love you the most and I always will.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://bp2.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RlJsl0cbF3I/AAAAAAAAABk/zEy-U80YfiQ/s1600-h/SOS_swell_4-27-070009.jpeg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://bp2.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RlJsl0cbF3I/AAAAAAAAABk/zEy-U80YfiQ/s400/SOS_swell_4-27-070009.jpeg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5067231927734048626" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://bp0.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RlJtXUcbF4I/AAAAAAAAABs/EXZ1E8MQQm0/s1600-h/sos5_19_070141.jpeg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://bp0.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RlJtXUcbF4I/AAAAAAAAABs/EXZ1E8MQQm0/s400/sos5_19_070141.jpeg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5067232778137573250" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://bp1.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RlJvUkcbF6I/AAAAAAAAAB8/GJVs33E8HTY/s1600-h/Astragalus_beckwithii_pods.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://bp1.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RlJvUkcbF6I/AAAAAAAAAB8/GJVs33E8HTY/s400/Astragalus_beckwithii_pods.jpg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5067234929916188578" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2007/05/i-still-love-you-astragalus.html' title='I still love you &lt;span style=&quot;font-style: italic;&quot;&gt;Astragalus&lt;/span&gt;'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=6275348070253493894&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/6275348070253493894/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/6275348070253493894'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/6275348070253493894'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-3350897135992135086</id><published>2007-05-09T20:25:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2007-05-10T11:19:25.103-07:00</updated><title type='text'>We'll have a Polygala Gala...</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://bp2.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RkKte1BLxyI/AAAAAAAAABc/zvsM_OJpNuU/s1600-h/img_0355.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://bp2.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RkKte1BLxyI/AAAAAAAAABc/zvsM_OJpNuU/s320/img_0355.jpg" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5062799676257584930" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You may remember &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Polygala subspinosa&lt;/span&gt; from last year. How could you forget? I never will. It is the most beautiful, the most elusive, the most sought after, the most frustrating plant in the world. &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Polygala subspinosa&lt;/span&gt; is my dream plant. And my nightmare.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I first met &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Polygala subspinosa&lt;/span&gt; at my Temple Mountain camp while looking at some &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Eriogonums&lt;/span&gt; and stuff. One morning, I walked around the corner of a Pinion pine and there were two very small, very beautiful plants with purple and yellow blossoms unfurling in the morning sun. That was all I needed to become completely obsessed. I spent the remainder of the summer criss-crossing the state, scrawled herbarium notes in hand, mumbling fuzzy map coordinates to myself, searching like a junkie for that one population that would go to Kew.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I never found more than half a dozen plants in one place. I would drive 50 miles out of my way, then scramble like a lemur all over an entire valley or mountainside to find one plant. One lone, beautiful plant. Taunting me. Holding those remarkable blossoms proudly above the thorny green mound below. It happened over and over and I became an utter mess. My friends stopped talking to me, my parents wrote me out of the will, I lost 30 pounds and hardly slept at all. When I finally hit rock bottom I had been dragging a plant press through the Wah Wah Mountains for 4 days without food or water and then collapsed face down in a pile of cow manure. A rancher saved me from suffocating to death and then talked some sense into me in that way that only a range-worn cowboy can. His leathery lips were glued shut most of the time, but when he chose to speak it was through complicated metaphors about the cattle, the range, the changing of seasons. It was deep, and I still don't completely understand all of what he said, but eventually I straightened out and gathered up the pieces of my shattered life, vowing never to lay eyes on another &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Polygala subspinosa&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;But today everything changed.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Someone named Deb, the Capitol Reef NP botanist, contacted me after seeing &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Polygala subspinosa&lt;/span&gt; on my Seeds of Success list. She told me about a population that she's seen in a place called Miner's Mountain. It should be blooming soon. It might be big enough to collect.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It might be.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It could go.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This time it could go....</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2007/05/well-have-polygala-gala.html' title='We&apos;ll have a &lt;span style=&quot;font-style:italic;&quot;&gt;Polygala&lt;/span&gt; Gala...'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=3350897135992135086&amp;isPopup=true' title='1 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/3350897135992135086/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/3350897135992135086'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/3350897135992135086'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-1613937082598409357</id><published>2007-01-18T20:55:00.000-08:00</published><updated>2007-05-10T10:54:12.123-07:00</updated><title type='text'>Thus begins the Year of the Buckwheat</title><content type='html'>Dear readers,&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;That would be the genus &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Eriogonum&lt;/span&gt; to those of you in the know, but the official name must start with a B since the 1st year of this blog was christened the Year of the &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Astragalus&lt;/span&gt;. Next year can be the Year of Compositae. Perhaps the &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Daleas&lt;/span&gt; in 2009?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It is official, I will be running a Utah Seeds of Success team again this year. I am excited, but field work is a long ways off. Today I went to work at the GIS lab, which tragically has not a single window to the outdoors, and I still found my brow dripping with perspiration because I was fantasizing on wandering through the desert, squeezing swelling buds, watching corollas part their lips to the desert breeze, nectar glistening in the morning sun, insects weaving drunkenly through the air laden with pollen grains. I am in an ecstatic dreamlike state. A transcendental walking meditation on native plants. And who will I wander the fields of flowers with this year? Maybe you dear reader... I am looking for a crack team of volunteers who are aroused by plant reproduction, the conservation thereof, and good human comeraderie in the wild west. Contact me if you can.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Here is the teaser for the next post: Its not even close to spring yet and most plants will be lying patiently dormant under a blanket of snow for at least a few months yet, so I will have to content myself with dreaming and doing research. To start, I'll be doing a little reading on &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Eriogonum&lt;/span&gt; - one of Utah's most diverse and beautiful plant genera. At this address you will soon find a brief treatise on the evolution and phylogeny of this group of plants to whet your whistle for the field season.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Yours, etc...&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Greg&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://bp2.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RbBoatsq8XI/AAAAAAAAAA0/y66B9uHN01I/s1600-h/Roancliffs.JPG"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://bp2.blogger.com/_GXjpWAjxWHA/RbBoatsq8XI/AAAAAAAAAA0/y66B9uHN01I/s400/Roancliffs.JPG" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5021628392670949746" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Somewhere in the Roan Cliffs&lt;/span&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2007/01/thus-begins-year-of-buckwheat.html' title='Thus begins the Year of the Buckwheat'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=1613937082598409357&amp;isPopup=true' title='1 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/1613937082598409357/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/1613937082598409357'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/1613937082598409357'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-116207324090450249</id><published>2006-10-28T14:38:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-11-13T18:49:48.583-08:00</updated><title type='text'>Current affairs at PVHD</title><content type='html'>Dear readers,&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I will post to this site occasionally over the winter, but my work with Red Butte Garden is on a seasonal break until we renew the Seeds of Success project next spring. We are working on getting the funding from BLM and CPC. Currently, I have a gig at the &lt;a href="http://www.sa.utah.edu/bennion/bend/"&gt;Bend-in-the-River&lt;/a&gt; doing riparian area restoration and am thinking of starting another blog about this. After all, you can never have too many blogs.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;To the Colorado resident who emailed me using the gregblogs@hotmail.com adress over the summer:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The hotmail staff erased my account due to a suspicion that I am not a real person and I subsequently lost your contact info. If you are still interested in seed exchange try the same email again. It should be OK now.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/Machaeranthera%20canescens%209-9-05%20044.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/400/Machaeranthera%20canescens%209-9-05%20044.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Machaeranthera canescens&lt;/span&gt;. Red Butte Natural Area</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/10/current-affairs-at-pvhd.html' title='Current affairs at PVHD'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=116207324090450249&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/116207324090450249/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/116207324090450249'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/116207324090450249'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-115886193026943773</id><published>2006-09-21T10:33:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2008-02-01T22:35:03.823-08:00</updated><title type='text'>Dodecatheon utahensis expedition - Year of Our Lord 2006</title><content type='html'>Last month, Matthew Utley, David Compton, Tara Poelzing, and I found a new population of a rare plant in Big Cottonwood Canyon. &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Dodecatheon utahensis&lt;/span&gt; (formerly &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Dodecatheon dentatum var. utahensis&lt;/span&gt;) grows only in a few locations in the canyon. It is a striking, magical little being that lives along seeps and waterfalls. We had a harrowing day finding it, but it all ended up being worthwhile.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Here are my journal entries for the day.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/IMG_0719.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/400/IMG_0719.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;7:00 am:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;It is a beautiful, sunny August morning in Big Cottonwood Canyon. The survey crew of 7 of the most eminent  botanists in the region has assembled at the base of the trial to Lake Blanch and there is animated discussion and convivial laugther while we drink our morning coffee and prepare to embark on our grand adventure in search of the rare and beautiful &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Dodecatheon utahensis&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;12:00 pm:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;After reaching the lake we split into 3 search parties and begin searching crevices and seeping overhangs in the quartzite cliff bands descending from the Sundial into the lake. After much searching there is still no sign of the &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Dodecatheon&lt;/span&gt;. Our energy is diminished, but spirits remain high and there is optimistic banter about finding our plant.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;2:00 pm: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Still nothing, and there are now some good natured arguments over routfinding and debates on what search areas to take on in order to make the most of the day. Rations are running low and some members of the crew begin to mention their afternoon engagements. Overall the mood is good though.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;2:45pm:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Half of the &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Dodecatheon&lt;/span&gt; search party turns back. The rest of us try to keep a positive attitude.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;3:30 pm:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It has become quite hot this afternoon and most of our water bottles are dry. There is more grumbling among the crew. Someone cracks a joke about mutiny. Uncomfortable laughter.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;4:25 pm:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The crew is now exhausted and patience is at an end. Some crew members are audibly and openly discussing mutiny. For my part, I have a swollen tongue, a cottony mouth, and am feeling very weary. I'm ready to give up. Someone mentions that Mr. David Compton parted with the group a while back.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;4:45 pm:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Mr. Compton has been missing for some 30 minutes now. Our search has left us emptyhanded, impatient, and dehydrated by this point and skeptics among us have now decided that the element occurrence that we are trying to verify was mistaken and that we are now on a wild goose chase with one unaccounted-for botanist already and more on the way if we don't turn around. There is also a faction of the group expressing frustration for Mister Compton and at some point the consensus becomes that he must be taught a lesson about "not being a douche and staying with the group" The crew makes plans to desert without him.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;4:46 pm: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Mr. Compton is sighted high above the crew, just beneath Sundial peak. He is gibbering unintelligibly and seems to be gesturing for the rest of the crew to hike up 1000 more vertical feet to join him. This is fiercely debated and there are violent outbursts among the crew. Threats and accusations fly.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;5:05 pm: &lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;After much argument and some minor scuffling among the crew, the decision is made to hike up to meet Mr. Compton. If he has duped us into climbing  this far with no sign of &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Dodecatheon &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;utahensis&lt;/span&gt; he will surely be lyched. The crew reluctantly begins the long trek up to the Sundial. There are periodic violent outbursts and many more complaints of dehydration.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;5:35 pm:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Exhausted, we reach Mr. Compton. He is grinning (in a somewhat oversatisfied manner in my opinion) and has found a striking population of the &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Dodecatheon&lt;/span&gt; perched high in a seeping overhang. The evening sun glistens on the tiny streams of water descending down the rock. We rejoice, collect all our field notes and site metrics, and then take a few pictures of the newest known population of Dodecatheon utahensis. As the crags across the canyon become bathed in whiskey colored light, we wrap up, pat each other on the backs, and head back.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;7:15 pm:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The crew retires to the Brighton Village Store and is rewarded by the orgnizer of this expedition with one 12 oz. beer each for their efforts. It is noted that this amounts to less than one ounce per hour of searching during the day. Laughter and much rejoicing follows.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/IMG_0727.0.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/400/IMG_0727.0.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/09/dodecatheon-utahensis-expedition-year.html' title='&lt;span style=&quot;font-style: italic;&quot;&gt;Dodecatheon utahensis&lt;/span&gt; expedition - Year of Our Lord 2006'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=115886193026943773&amp;isPopup=true' title='2 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/115886193026943773/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115886193026943773'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115886193026943773'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-115690321198327694</id><published>2006-08-29T18:56:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-08-29T19:08:24.013-07:00</updated><title type='text'>Former glory</title><content type='html'>This blog will soon be restored to it's former glory and influence. It may be retooled and repurposed as well. Seeds of Success has come to an end for this year, but there are a few more SOS stories to tell, plus others. I am currently on sabattical from blogging for another week or so. Sit tight.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0694.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/400/img_0694.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Carex utriculata&lt;/span&gt;. Trout Creek, UT.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/08/former-glory.html' title='Former glory'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=115690321198327694&amp;isPopup=true' title='2 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/115690321198327694/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115690321198327694'/><lin