 send up such big, showy flower heads. But why were you so stingy with the seeds this year?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0358.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0358.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Frasera albomarginata&lt;/span&gt;: You are one weird looking plant. I couldn't figure out what you were for the longest time. Next year we'll give you more time to set seed.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0559.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0559.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Abronia fragrans&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;nana&lt;/span&gt;: You two are great. I'm sure the perfect Sand verbena year is coming before the apocalypse, and when it does, I expect the San Rafael Desert and the DER to be blanketed in in your blossoms.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0452.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0452.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Encelia frutescens&lt;/span&gt;: You are totally hot. We'll be seeing more of you next year. Call your friends.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0282.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0282.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Penstemon utahensis&lt;/span&gt;: Sorry, but sometimes botanists don't want to drive all the way to Moab on the off chance that you got a little moisture and made another halfhearted attempt to flower. Lets try a little harder next season, eh?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/imgp2266.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/imgp2266.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Penstemon fremontii&lt;/span&gt;: Why did I drive all over the Uintah Basin looking for another freaking blue penstemon? Is it hopeless? Do you even exist?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;Well! Do you?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/07/more-plants-we-will-admire-from-afar.html' title='More plants we will admire from afar (until next year)'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=115336011894756385&amp;isPopup=true' title='3 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/115336011894756385/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115336011894756385'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115336011894756385'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-115303186602076998</id><published>2006-07-16T23:31:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-07-20T18:53:29.710-07:00</updated><title type='text'>Please don't wipe with America's natural heritage!</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0628.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0pt 10px 10px 0pt; float: left; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0628.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Oh &lt;a href="http://www.utahrareplants.org/jpg/Caesalpinia_repens_p1.png" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Caesalpinia repens&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;!&lt;br /&gt;You are so &lt;a href="http://www.utahrareplants.org/jpg/Caesalpinia_repens_p2.jpg" target="_blank"&gt;beautiful&lt;/a&gt;, and so rare&lt;br /&gt;With your little bird of paradise flowers.&lt;br /&gt;And so imperiled at a &lt;a href="http://www.natureserve.org/explorer/ranking.htm" target="_blank"&gt;G2 rating&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Your pinnate leaves unfurl in only 5 Utah counties&lt;br /&gt;So beautifully that Stan Welsh called you a&lt;br /&gt;"striking plant in the light of early morning"&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Oh Bureau of Land Management!&lt;br /&gt;You are such a wonderful government agency.&lt;br /&gt;A bureau so nice and careful and smart.&lt;br /&gt;You treat your valuable little plants so well&lt;br /&gt;Like when you closed the overused camping area&lt;br /&gt;And moved it across the road&lt;br /&gt;To where the rare little &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Caesalpinias&lt;/span&gt; are.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Oh Eagle Scout Troop!&lt;br /&gt;You built such a nice new camping area&lt;br /&gt;With shiny new bathrooms and fire barrels&lt;br /&gt;And all the lovely imperiled plants around.&lt;br /&gt;So that people who love rare little &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Caesalpinias&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Can go camping with them now&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;And sing them campfire songs at night&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;And wake up early to see the &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Caesalpinias&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;being so striking in the light of early morning.&lt;br /&gt;Little &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Caesalpinias&lt;/span&gt; won't be so lonely anymore.&lt;br /&gt;People love looking at nice little rare plants&lt;br /&gt;When they are walking to the shiny new bathroom&lt;br /&gt;To take care of their morning business.&lt;br /&gt;And if someone found out too late that there is no more TP?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;America's natural heritage is right outside the door&lt;br /&gt;Looking so striking in the light of early morning...&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You wouldn't wipe with a handfull the American flag, would you?&lt;br /&gt;or the Constitution?&lt;br /&gt;or a bald eagle?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Would you?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0626.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0626.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt; Caesalpinia repens, baffled botanist, shiny new bathroom.&lt;/span&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/07/please-dont-wipe-with-americas-natural.html' title='Please don&apos;t wipe with America&apos;s natural heritage!'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=115303186602076998&amp;isPopup=true' title='5 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/115303186602076998/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115303186602076998'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115303186602076998'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-115284146082201585</id><published>2006-07-13T18:17:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-07-16T18:05:40.800-07:00</updated><title type='text'>The winds of change just blew sand in my eyes</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/POINhabitat.0.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0pt 0pt 10px 10px; float: right; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/200/POINhabitat.0.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;San Rafael Desert dunes stabilized by Poliomintha incana and Quercus welshii.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Good evening all, a few weeks ago I made passing reference to plants that stabilize sand dunes and how important they are. I was referring, in part, to our lovely &lt;a href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0344.jpg"&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Poliomintha incana&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; species. And though that plant may elude us as a Millenium Seed Bank species due to lackluster seed production and a lack of manpower this year, I still think it is important to talk about why &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Poliomintha incana&lt;/span&gt; and other sand stabilizing plants are becoming so intriguing in these crazy times that we live in. So, gather all your tender minds around the monitor - its time for the POVHAD blog to teach you some stuff.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In the aforementioned post I posted a link to an &lt;a href="http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5415315" target="_blank"&gt;NPR feature on windblown dust&lt;/a&gt; in the Southwest. The feature talked about how, particularly in Utah, airborne dust is on the rise due to the decline of biotic soil crusts. These soil crusts, which stabilize large areas of fine textured soils in Utah, are in decline mainly due to human activites such as ORV use and grazing activity, and the resulting increases in blowing dust has a variety of problematic consequences. (&lt;a href="http://www.soilcrust.org/" target="_blank"&gt;USGS soil crust site&lt;/a&gt;). Well, a close relative of windblown dust, is windblown sand, and as I was taking cowardly refuge in my pickup truck during a severe San Rafael Desert sandstorm I was inspired to learn more about windblown sand and the plant communities growing in this sandblasted ecosystem.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;*  *  *&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0544.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0pt 10px 10px 0pt; float: left; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/200/img_0544.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Unknown, San Rafael Desert.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;For the purpose of this discussion, let's talk about what is needed to make sand dunes, and then define two types of sand dunes. The two critical factors that make dunes possible are a plentiful source of sand, and strong, frequent winds to blow the sand. There are many geologic formations that weather into sand, (usually sandstones) and no shortage of wind in many parts of the arid West, making this a good place for dunes. The first type of dunes are active sand dunes - large areas of windblown (or eolian) sands that are actively moving. Though such dunes may not appear to move, perhaps remaining in a natural depression like a valley, the sand nevertheless moves with each wind storm to form fresh patterns and features in the dunes. The physical aspects of active sand dune formation and movement are &lt;a href="http://www.nps.gov/whsa/Sand%20Dune%20Geology.htm" target="_blank"&gt;discussed here&lt;/a&gt;. In an active dune environment, the constant churning of sand allows little chance for vegetation to establish and makes these areas unsuitable for human habitation, agriculture and grazing. The second dune type - stabilized dunes -  are large areas of surface sand, often in sheets, that are not actively moving or changing shape, at least not on a large scale. The reason for these dunes' stability is that they support the growth of vegetation. Not just little annuals either, but strongly rooted perennials and shrubs. Though the wind may blow, the plants that grow here can hold on and anchor a well developed community of organisms.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Active dunes are common in the the Sonoran, Mojave, and Chihuahuan deserts of North America, but with a few &lt;a href="http://www.desertusa.com/coralut/corut.html" target="_blank"&gt;exceptions&lt;/a&gt;, there aren't many active sand dunes on the Colorado Plateau. This is in spite of the fact that places like the San Rafael Desert have both an abundant source of sand - the layercake sandstones of the region thrust out of the ground everywhere - and reliable strong winds. I have rarely visited Hanksville or Moab without griping for at least a few hours in stiff to howling winds. However, the dunes here are almost always stabilized by vegetation. The difference, as you might have guessed, is moisture. The &lt;a href="http://www.cpluhna.nau.edu/Change/modern_climatic_conditions.htm" target="_blank"&gt;Colorado Plateau&lt;/a&gt; recieves just slightly more moisture than the &lt;a href="http://helios.bto.ed.ac.uk/bto/desertecology/northame.htm#top" target="_blank"&gt;deserts mentioned above&lt;/a&gt;, allowing plants to gain a solid foothold in the sand.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0551.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0551.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;I counted eleven unique insect species on this one milkweed plant.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The dunes of the San Rafael Desert are stabilized by a diverse community of beautiful and unique plants and it is well worth a visit during the spring or early summer. In addition, there is a huge diversity of insects and larger wildlife such as lizards, rabbits, prarie dogs, and pronghorn antelope. A few of the interesting plants you might find there:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Amsonia tomentosa&lt;/span&gt; - &lt;a href="http://www.calflora.net/bloomingplants/woollyamsonia.html" target="_blank"&gt;Wooly Amsonia&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Artemisia filifolia - &lt;/span&gt;Old man sagebrush&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Quercus welshii&lt;/span&gt; - a &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;gambellii/turbinella&lt;/span&gt; hybrid that stabilizes dunes.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Ephedra sp.&lt;/span&gt; - Mormon tea&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Wyethia scabra&lt;/span&gt; - Rough mulear sunflower&lt;br /&gt;A wild assortment of Milkweeds, Flax, Phacelia, Asters, Globemallows, Astragalus, Lupine, Penstemon, and Sand verbenas.&lt;br /&gt;And of course our lovely &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Poliomintha incana&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;So, asking what the future holds for a stabilized dune ecosystem that recieves only a fraction more moisture on average than nearby active dune ecosystem seems like a relevant question to ask, especially in the era of human caused climate change. The USGS seems to think that there is a potential for large areas of stable dunes in the southwest to become active again, perhaps rendering large sections of Navajo and Hopi land in the Four Corners region uninhabitable (&lt;a href="http://geochange.er.usgs.gov/sw/impacts/geology/sand/" target="_blank"&gt;USGS site&lt;/a&gt;.) According to them, even a slight drying of the climate might make plant communities such as the one in the San Rafael Desert recede, leaving large tracts of active dunes. Such a phenomenon is already a part of widespread desertification happening in &lt;a href="http://www.worldchanging.com/archives/000252.html" target="_blank"&gt;northern China&lt;/a&gt;, Hopefully, we will be able to manage such a crisis before it gets so bad, and learning more about dune stabilizing plants might be a small part of that. Incidentally, 2006 is the &lt;a href="http://www.iydd.org/" target="_blank"&gt;International Year of Deserts and Desertification&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;*  *  *&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Before the sky turned a murky brown and I scrambledblindly into the truck I saw great clouds of sand, lit yellow from behind, rise out of the valley between Wild Horse Butte and the Reef. I watched all the shrubs and bunchgrasses rolling over under waves of wind, and then hunker down to the ground to endure a good sandblasting. My truck started to shake back and forth. It was beautiful.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0629.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0629.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;San Rafael Desert, Gilson Buttes and the Henries in distance.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/07/winds-of-change-just-blew-sand-in-my.html' title='The winds of change just blew sand in my eyes'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=115284146082201585&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/115284146082201585/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115284146082201585'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115284146082201585'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-115225935328139880</id><published>2006-07-07T00:22:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-07-07T01:06:23.703-07:00</updated><title type='text'>What do I keep in my long, slender, damselfly abdomen?</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0582.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0582.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;a. Sewing needle&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;b. Cotton swab&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;c. Primary and secondary genitalia structures&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;d. Caudal lamellae&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;answer: c and d.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Caudal lamellae are respiratory/ventilatory structures present on the abdomen in the aquatic larval stage of a damselfly.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;During mating, male damselflies curl their abdomens forward to deposit sperm on an external secondary genitalia structure. The male then clasps the female damselfly to his body and the two fly around in this coupled formation, often for several hours. In this time she curls her abdomen forward to pick up the male's sperm and fertilize her eggs. When mating is over, the pair may fly in tandem until the female can deposit eggs into aquatic vegetation or directly into the water.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The couples I saw were too shy to land and let me take a picture to publish on the internet.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/07/what-do-i-keep-in-my-long-slender.html' title='What do I keep in my long, slender, damselfly abdomen?'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=115225935328139880&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/115225935328139880/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115225935328139880'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115225935328139880'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-115225520596995059</id><published>2006-07-06T23:53:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-07-07T01:26:07.916-07:00</updated><title type='text'>Recent love affairs and plants we will admire from afar</title><content type='html'>*sigh*&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;botany, like other kinds of romance, can break your heart. we found these.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0603.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0603.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Carex hoodii&lt;/span&gt; at daybreak on Trout Creek Ridge.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0519.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0519.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Claytonia lanceolata&lt;/span&gt;, Lanceleaf Spring Beauty. Trout Creek Ridge.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0572.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0572.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Mentzelia laevicaulis.&lt;/span&gt; Smoothstem blazingstar. Wah Wah Mountains.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0579.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0579.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Penstemon rostriflorus&lt;/span&gt;, Bridge penstemon with pollenator. Wah Wah Mountains. Someday....</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/07/recent-love-affairs-and-plants-we-will.html' title='Recent love affairs and plants we will admire from afar'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=115225520596995059&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/115225520596995059/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115225520596995059'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115225520596995059'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-115146695970233759</id><published>2006-06-27T19:54:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-07-31T09:09:51.610-07:00</updated><title type='text'>Trials and tribulations of field botanists in the "Year of the Astragalus"</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0563.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0pt 0pt 10px 10px; float: right; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/200/img_0563.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Intrepid botanists on the road back to camp for the night.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;People, I'm really trying to stay above the once a week blogging threshold. But alas, it can be difficult to come up with witty stories and mind-boggling photographs on a regular basis, especially while assuming the herculean task of finding and collecting huge amounts of native plant seed in the far flung locales of the Beehive State. I hope that the unbelievably high quality of the individual posts will make up for the sometimes painfully long (for the reader) periods in between them.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Now to the subject of today's post:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Matthew and I rocked the proverbial house last week on a two day collecting stint in the Swell. We collected another two members of &lt;span style="font-style:italic;"&gt;Astragalus&lt;/span&gt; -&lt;span style="font-style:italic;"&gt;praelongus&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span style="font-style:italic;"&gt;moencoppensis&lt;/span&gt;- for Kew, got a huge collection of Singleleaf ash for the Bend seed bank, and a somewhat disappointing collection from &lt;span style="font-style:italic;"&gt;Poliomintha incana&lt;/span&gt;. The kicker though, was a whopping 10 collections that will go to the Red Butte Garden seed bank for trials. Granted, these are small collections and it wasn't that hard to get 10 done, but they are all fantastic species with great horticultural potential. With any luck you will be seeing them in the RB Gardens in the next few years. With even more luck, some may make it out of Red Butte Gardens and into the gardens of the world - maybe even yours - in the years to come.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:bold;"&gt;Here are a few of my faves for the trial program:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0362.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0362.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Linum puberulum, a beautiful, delicate little flax growing in open Pinion-Juniper table-lands.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0310.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0310.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Eriogonum bicolor, Pretty buckwheat. I can't believe I havent shown a pic of this in bloom yet.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0299.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0299.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Syphoricarpos longiflorus, Longflower snowberry. A big, flowing shrub that should do well in hot, dry shade.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style="font-weight:bold;"&gt;Closing thoughts:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Considering the enormous success we're having collecting &lt;span style="font-style:italic;"&gt;Astragalus&lt;/span&gt;, I'd like to  name 2006 the "Year of the &lt;span style="font-style:italic;"&gt;Astragalus&lt;/span&gt;." If 2007 is as favorable as I'm hoping it will be, I'd like to call it the "Year of the &lt;span style="font-style:italic;"&gt;Eriogonum&lt;/span&gt;." I think it would be great to have this become a tradition for everyone at Red Butte (at least), with a new genus introduced and celebrated with great fanfare every May. Perhaps there could even be a parade down the Floral Walk as the opening event for the plant sale or something. Will someone bring this up at the next staff meeting for me please?</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/06/trials-and-tribulations-of-field.html' title='Trials and tribulations of field botanists in the &quot;Year of the Astragalus&quot;'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=115146695970233759&amp;isPopup=true' title='1 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/115146695970233759/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115146695970233759'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115146695970233759'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-115087139237705123</id><published>2006-06-20T23:14:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-06-21T06:01:12.760-07:00</updated><title type='text'>This blog: Is it the future of the botanical media?</title><content type='html'>There has been much discussion lately about the emerging blogosphere's imminent role in revolutionizing "the news" and overtaking the "mainsteam media" as the public's main source of information about the world around them. Though we here at the "; plants of various habit and distribution........" blog elected NOT to attend the &lt;a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/09/washington/09cnd-bloggers.html?ex=1151035200&amp;en=e24c00e31e4c7c08&amp;amp;ei=5070" target="_blank"&gt;first annual meeting of the progressive blogosphere&lt;/a&gt; at the &lt;a href="http://www.yearlykos.org/" target="_blank"&gt;YearlyKos&lt;/a&gt; convention in Las Vegas, NV last week, we would nonetheless like to add our two cents to all the fuss. We see ourselves as martyrs for "the cause", and given the staggering growth in readership since our inception, we think the entire world will take note.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In a sense, we owe a debt of gratitude to the "mainstream media" for ignoring the key issues, such as &lt;a href="http://tncweeds.ucdavis.edu/index.html" target="_blank"&gt;invasive plant species&lt;/a&gt;, the phenomenon known as "&lt;a href="http://utahseeds.blogspot.com/2006/05/case-of-head-bonking-cows-revisited.html" target="_blank"&gt;locoweeds&lt;/a&gt;", human &lt;a href="http://www.centerforplantconservation.org/ASP/CPC_ViewProfile.asp?CPCNum=205" target="_blank"&gt;encroachment into native plant communities&lt;/a&gt;, and the effects of global warming (&lt;a href="http://scholar.google.com/url?sa=U&amp;q=http://www.erin.utoronto.ca/%7Ew3pkota/courses/bot1700/dukes%26mooney1999.pdf"&gt;pdf&lt;/a&gt;) that are already being felt in ecosystems around the globe. Their ineptitude has opened a whole universe of crucial issues for us to report and offer carefully considered editorials on. Though we too will mourn the disappearance of current events printed on old fashioned dead plant fibers with (sometimes) soy derived inks, we hope that the tradeoff will be for accuracy in reporting on issues that matter to plants, and by association, all the organisms in this community that we know as Earth.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You, our loyal readers, can rest assured knowing that this blog will continue take the lead in reporting most current, prescient, and accurate stories in the plant world. Thanks for reading.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/Juncus%20arcticus%206-10-05%283%29.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/Juncus%20arcticus%206-10-05%283%29.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Juncus arcticus&lt;/span&gt;, Wiregrass - stigmas fully extended. Red Butte Gardens Natural Area.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/06/this-blog-is-it-future-of-botanical.html' title='This blog: Is it the future of the botanical media?'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=115087139237705123&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/115087139237705123/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115087139237705123'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115087139237705123'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-115078119956411299</id><published>2006-06-19T22:22:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-07-08T09:49:22.433-07:00</updated><title type='text'>A hairy caterpillar</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0520.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0520.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Hackelia floribunda with a visitor. Trout Creek Ridge, UT.&lt;/span&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/06/hairy-caterpillar.html' title='A hairy caterpillar'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=115078119956411299&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/115078119956411299/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115078119956411299'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115078119956411299'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-115025447336879539</id><published>2006-06-13T19:55:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-06-14T15:30:50.166-07:00</updated><title type='text'>Visiting the Desert Experimental Range</title><content type='html'>&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Enter the Desert Experimental Range - no human-animal hybrids here. Tunnel Springs Range in background.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0433.0.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0433.0.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;When I saw a "Desert Experimental Range" on the map, sprawled out in a desolate valley near the Utah-Nevada border, I had visions of top secret flying machines and pens full of human-animal hybrids. Of course I had to find out the truth, and finding out if the place could somehow be productive for the Seeds of Success program was the perfect in. The truth about the &lt;a href="http://www.fs.fed.us/rm/provo/desert_range/desert_range.shtml" target="_blank"&gt;Desert Experimental Range&lt;/a&gt;, which is not classified, secret, or scary in any way, is this: it is a 225 square km plot of land that has been set aside for range management and ecology research. The research done here can help improve land management techniques for the 200,000 square km of land in the Great Basin that are floristically and geologically similar to the DER.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0466.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0pt 0pt 10px 10px; float: right; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/200/img_0466.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Prunus fasciculata, Desert almond. Evidently, fruit production is rare here.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The DER was set aside in 1933 by President Herbert Hoover. At this time, as the Great Depression was beginning, the public lands of the West and especially the Great Basin had been under intensive use for grazing for some time. This unmanaged use was beginning to take a toll on the landscape, the health of the plant communities, and the productivity of the region's livestock industry. Hoover set aside the DER as an "agricultural range experiment station" to encourage research into rangeland ecology of the Great Basin, and to develop more sustainable livestock practices. To this end, the DER was fenced by the Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC) in 1935 and portions of the land were divided into various enclosures and exclosures so that grazing regimes and management techniques could be tested and the results observed on a long term basis.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;"Sheep grazing studies began in the winter of 1934/1935 to study the economic and ecological impacts of grazing at different intensities, seasons, and frequencies. The core of those grazing treatments has been maintained each winter for 59 years. Cattle grazing was added later. Several permanent exclosures ranging in size from 0.4 to 740 ha (1.0 to 1828 acres) are scattered throughout the Desert Experimental Range on all plant community types permitting direct examination of the effects of grazing and nonuse." --from Desert Experimental Range publication, Stanley G. Kitchen and E. Durant McArthur.&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0439.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0pt 10px 10px 0pt; float: left; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/200/img_0439.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;DER post office. Wah Wah Mountains in distance.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In1976 the DER was incorporated into the &lt;a href="http://www.unesco.org/mab/mabProg.shtml" target="_blank"&gt;UNESCO Man and the Biosphere&lt;/a&gt; programme's network of reserves, representing the worlds cold-desert biomes. The purpose of MAB reserves is to encourage research on how humankind interacts with its environment with goals of reducing biodiversity loss, improving livelihoods, and enhancing social, economic and cultural conditions for environmental                  sustainability. The DER is one of approximately 480 reserves set aside in 100 countries around the world to represent all the world's biomes.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;"The Man and the Biosphere Programme (MAB), proposes                an interdisciplinary research agenda and capacity building aiming                to improve the relationship of people with their environment globally.                Launched in the early 1970s, it notably targets the ecological,                social and economic dimensions of biodiversity loss and the reduction                of this loss. It uses its World Network of Biosphere Reserves as                vehicles for knowledge-sharing, research and monitoring, education                and training, and participatory decision-making." -- From UNESCO's MAB website.&lt;/blockquote&gt;Thanks to Stan for making my visit more productive.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0456.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0456.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Sphaeralcea caespitosa, Tufted globemallow. Endemic to the DER and nearby areas.&lt;/span&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/06/visiting-desert-experimental-range.html' title='Visiting the Desert Experimental Range'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=115025447336879539&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/115025447336879539/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115025447336879539'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/115025447336879539'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-115013312212673215</id><published>2006-06-12T08:55:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-06-12T13:40:53.636-07:00</updated><title type='text'>A hot harvest, while sniffing the winds of change</title><content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0498.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0498.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Kevin and 20,000 Astragalus rafaelensis seeds, Calf Canyon, UT&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Its getting to be harvest time! Just returned from a brilliant 2 day trip to the Swell with some members of our fine RBG Volunteer Corps. Together we harvested 3 Kew collections - &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Astragalus rafaelensis, Astragalus woodruffi, &lt;/span&gt;and &lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Gaillardia spathulata. &lt;/span&gt;Many thanks to Jenn, Jake, and Kevin for all the help out there under the unforgiving sun.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We also got a smaller collection of &lt;a href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0344.jpg" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Poliomintha incana&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/a&gt;done, but we might have to try again later for a larger collection of this one. It has a lovely minty sage scent, making it a pleasure to collect, and outstanding horticultural potential, but it also has the difficult job of stabilizing sand dunes in a very windy area. Given this valuable ecological role and the ongoing process of climate change, it may be an increasingly important species to collect for restoration purposes. I'm going to put together an educational post about eolian (windblown) sand, vegetation, and climate change soon, but as a teaser, see this &lt;a href="http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5415315" target="_blank"&gt;feature on dust in Utah&lt;/a&gt; from NPR. Hopefully all the Hoary Desert Rosemary-mint seed wont get sandblasted away in the next few weeks.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0499.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0499.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&