ate.html' title='Sidebar update!'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=114973245796075517&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/114973245796075517/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/114973245796075517'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/114973245796075517'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-114961369876239407</id><published>2006-06-06T10:04:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-06-06T11:35:00.513-07:00</updated><title type='text'>Plant science: the most exciting occupation on Earth?</title><content type='html'>From an excellent article in the NY Times about forest ecologists:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;Researchers still trek into the field to record the numbers. In the seedling census now under way on Barro Colorado, young biologists doing the tallies bound like ocelots up the steep path above Laboratory Cove through an idyllic forest where howler monkeys dangle and orchid bees hover. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;At other plots, stretched around the Equator like a belt, plot science takes on Indiana Jones dimensions. Deep in the forest, scientists can encounter tropical diseases, toxic ant bites, spitting cobras, smugglers and armed insurgents. More than one scientist from the forest center has had a close call.&lt;/blockquote&gt;</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/06/plant-science-most-exciting-occupation.html' title='Plant science: the most exciting occupation on Earth?'/><link rel='related' href='http://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/06/science/earth/06tree.html?pagewanted=1' title='Plant science: the most exciting occupation on Earth?'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=114961369876239407&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/114961369876239407/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/114961369876239407'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/114961369876239407'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-26070657.post-114961181963676781</id><published>2006-06-06T08:35:00.000-07:00</published><updated>2006-06-06T09:42:43.433-07:00</updated><title type='text'>Great Basin wildflowers</title><content type='html'>Last week I took a trip out to the basin and range country of southwest Utah to look for plants. Here are a few photos from the Wah Wah mountains and Pine Valley -- not all are keyed out yet. While down there I paid a visit to the Desert Experimental Range, which I'll talk about in a later post.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0417.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0417.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;Escobaria vivipara var. vivipara&lt;/span&gt;, spinystar, Wah Wah Mtns&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0413.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0413.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt; Eriogonum sp. &lt;/span&gt;Wah Wah Mountains&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/1600/img_0443.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="margin: 0px auto 10px; display: block; text-align: center; cursor: pointer;" src="http://photos1.blogger.com/blogger/4587/2729/320/img_0443.jpg" alt="" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-style: italic;"&gt; Phacelia crenulata&lt;/span&gt;, Desert phacelia/scorpionweed, Pine Valley.</content><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/2006/06/great-basin-wildflowers.html' title='Great Basin wildflowers'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://www.blogger.com/comment.g?blogID=26070657&amp;postID=114961181963676781&amp;isPopup=true' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://blog.primaryproductivity.org/feeds/114961181963676781/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/114961181963676781'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/26070657/posts/default/114961181963676781'/><author><name>Greg</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/11511247372356785100</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email></author></entry></feed>